  "prompt": "What is a zero sum game?",
  "response": "A zero-sum game is a mathematical representation of a situation in which an advantage gained by one participant is exactly balanced by the losses of other participants. In other words, the total amount of resources, benefits, or payoff available in the system is fixed, so any gain by one player must be matched by an equal loss by others. This concept is often used in game theory and economics to describe competitive situations where the interests of participants are directly opposed. \n\nClassic examples of zero-sum games include games like poker and chess, where the winnings for one player equal the losses for another. In economics, certain market situations may be modeled as zero-sum, although real-life interactions often involve elements of positive-sum or negative-sum outcomes, where the total payoff can increase or decrease due to cooperation, inefficiencies, or external factors.",
